______________________________________________________

Phase 1: Compilation Stage
Lexical Analysis (Tokenization) – The source code is broken into tokens 
(keywords, identifiers, operators, etc.).
Parsing – Tokens are organized into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST), and 
syntax/indentation errors are checked.
Bytecode Generation – The compiler converts the AST into platform-independent bytecode.
Caching (.pyc File) – The bytecode is stored in the __pycache__ folder as a .pyc file 
for faster execution next time.

Phase 2: Interpretation Stage
Python Virtual Machine (PVM) – The PVM reads and executes the bytecode instruction by
 instruction.
Machine Translation – The PVM converts bytecode into machine instructions specific to 
the operating system during execution.
Runtime Execution & Errors – The program runs, and if a runtime error occurs 
(e.g., division by zero or undefined variable), 
Python stops execution and displays an error message.

Source Code (.py) → Tokenization → Parsing (AST) → Bytecode → 
.pyc Cache → PVM → Machine Code → Output/Error
